Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are the source of the bug?

router

### Is this a regression?

No

### Description

When using `withComponentInputBinding()` in Angular 19 to bind route parameters to a component‚Äôs signal-based `input()`, the binding works correctly during in-app navigation but fails when navigating directly to a deep link. Specifically, the signal input remains `undefined` on initial load via a deep link, while it updates as expected when navigating within the app.

### Current Behavior
- Navigating directly to a deep link (e.g., `/server/id/foo`) results in the component‚Äôs `id` signal input being `undefined`.
- Navigating within the app (e.g., from `/server/id/foo` to `/server/id/bar`) correctly updates the `id` signal input to the new value (e.g., `bar`).

### Expected Behavior
- The id signal input should be set to the route parameter value (e.g., 123) when loading the app via a deep link, just as it does during in-app navigation.

## Minimal Reproduction
1. Create a new Angular 19 project: `ng new repro --standalone`.
2. Configure the router with `withComponentInputBinding()` in `app.config.ts`:
```typescript
import { provideRouter, withComponentInputBinding } from '@angular/router';
import { routes } from './app.routes';

export const appConfig = {
  providers: [provideRouter(routes, withComponentInputBinding())]
};
```
3. Define a route in `app.routes.ts`:
```typescript
import { Routes } from '@angular/router';
import { LdapServersTabComponent } from './ldap-servers-tab.component';

export const routes: Routes = [
  { path: 'server/id/:id', component: ChildComponent }
];
```
4. Create a component `child.component.ts`:
```typescript
import { Component, input, effect } from '@angular/core';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    <p>ID: {{ id() }}</p>
    <a routerLink="server/id/foo">foo</a>
    <a routerLink="/server/id/bar">bar</a>
  `,
})
export class ChildComponent {
  id = input<string>();
  idEffect = effect(() => console.log('ID:', this.id()));
}
```
5. Start the app: `ng serve`.
6. Test the following:
- Navigate to `http://localhost:4200/server/id/foo` directly (deep link): `id()` logs `undefined`.
- Navigate within the app to `/server/id/bar` (e.g., via a `<a routerLink="/server/id/bar">` link): `id()` logs `bar`.

## Steps to Reproduce
1. Follow the minimal reproduction steps above.
2. Open the browser console to observe the `id()` value.
3. Compare behavior between deep link navigation and in-app navigation.

## Environment
- Angular Version: 19.2.3
- Node Version: 20
- OS: macOS 15
- Browser: Edge, reproducible in all major browsers

## Possible Cause
This might be a timing issue during initial app bootstrap where the router resolves the route before the component‚Äôs signal inputs are fully initialized, or a limitation in `withComponentInputBinding()` when handling deep links.

## Workaround
Manually fetch the parameter using `ActivatedRoute`:
```typescript
import { Component, input, effect } from '@angular/core';
import { ActivatedRoute } from '@angular/router';

@Component({
  selector: 'app-child',
  standalone: true,
  template: `
    <p>ID: {{ id() }}</p>
    <a routerLink="server/id/foo">foo</a>
    <a routerLink="/server/id/bar">bar</a>
  `,
})
export class ChildComponent {
  id = input<string>();
  actualId: string;

  constructor(private route: ActivatedRoute) {
    this.actualId = this.route.snapshot.paramMap.get('id') || this.id();
  }

  idEffect = effect(() => console.log('ID:', this.id() || this.actualId));
}
```

## Additional Context
- This issue impacts apps relying on deep linking for SEO or direct URL sharing.
- The `effect()` logs demonstrate the discrepancy clearly in the console.
- I couldn‚Äôt find an existing issue exactly matching this behavior in Angular 19, but it may relate to prior input binding discussions.

## Suggested Fix
Ensure `withComponentInputBinding()` initializes signal inputs with route parameters during the initial bootstrap process, matching the behavior of in-app navigation.

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

`@angular/core`

### Description

Currently the method is in private API, but I'd like to extend and modify it:
https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/aa45d44c5bee49638534895e8650dd3a9217e553/packages/core/src/application/application_init.ts#L238-L239

Usecase:
While optimizing TBT Web Vital of my app, I'd like to split apart a few parts of the application bootstrap process. As one of them I'd like to split apart running all the `APP_INITIALIZER`s to a separate macrotask. For this usecase I'd like to overwrite the `runInitializers()` method of `ApplicationInitiStatus` class and run its original implementation via `setTimeout()`:

```ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CustomApplicationInitStatus extends ApplicationInitStatus {
  runInitializers() {
    setTimeout(() => {
      // @ts-ignore - CAUTION - DIRTY WORKAROUND! THIS METHOD IS PRIVATE
      super.runInitializers();
    }, 0);
  }
}
```

Unfortunately, the method `runInitializers()` is in private API so I cannot safely extend it and my code might break during any minor/patch release of Angular, which I could not accept.

Please note that the whole class `ApplicationInitStatus` is already in public API and extendable (able to over-provide). It's only the method `runInitializers()` that is troublesome to extend with confidence.

### Proposed solution

Make `runInitializers()` method public

### Alternatives considered

### Workaround 1 - use a private method
```ts
@Injectable({ providedIn: 'root' })
export class CustomApplicationInitStatus extends ApplicationInitStatus {
  runInitializers() {
    setTimeout(() => {
      // @ts-ignore - CAUTION - DIRTY WORKAROUND! THIS METHOD IS PRIVATE
      super.runInitializers();
    }, 0);
  }
}

/* ... */
{
  provide: ApplicationInitStatus,
  useExisting: CustomApplicationInitStatus,
},
```
- pros: short implementation
- cons: can break in any release due to using a private Angular API

### Workaround 2 - introduce `CUSTOM_APP_INITIALIZER` injection token
Don't over-provide `ApplicationInitiStatus`
Introduce your custom `CUSTOM_APP_INITIALIZER` (multi) injection token and use it everywhere instead of `APP_INITIALIZER`
Provide one real `APP_INITIALIZER` that executes and combines promises from all `CUSTOM_APP_INITIALIZER`s - similarly to how [`ApplicationInitStatus.runInitializers` executes and combines promises from all `APP_INITIAIZER`s](https://github.com/angular/angular/blob/aa45d44c5bee49638534895e8650dd3a9217e553/packages/core/src/application/application_init.ts#L263)

- pros: doesn't rely on private API
- cons: cannot change other 3rd party libraries which already use `APP_INITIALIZER` to use my `CUSTOM_APP_INITIALIZER`

Moves tokens out of `core/tokens` and into their respective component directories.

Also uses a new `token-utils.slot()` function that replaces `create-tokens-slot`:

```
// Before:
.mat-comp {
  @include token-utils.create-token-slot(border-radius, container-shape);
}

// After:
.mat-comp {
  border-radius: token-utils.slot(container-shape);
}
```
